         "id": "prerequisites",
         "desc": "",
         "target": "",
         "page": "",
         "value_type": "",
         "html_value": "<p class=\"topdesc\"><i>The abbreviations A.E.C, B.C.E (Before Common Era), and negative years serve as generalizations for representing eras preceding the initial days of the calendars.</i></p><p class=\"topdesc\"><i>In addition to using the name America, we will also refer to the continent as <i>Abya Yala</i>, a term used by the indigenous peoples of the continent (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('160fb48c-1711-491e-a1aa-e1257e7889af'); return false;\">Porto-Gon√ßalves, Carlos Walter, <htdate0>, pp. 39-43</a>).</i></p><p><h3>Prerequisites</h3>Studying genealogy requires knowledge from various sciences. To gain a deeper understanding of all texts, we suggest first studying the following sections:</p><p><ul><li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e'); return false;\">First steps:</a> some texts from the Science section are rewritten here in a more engaging way. This section also contains the fundamentals necessary for a complete understanding of the Science section.</li><li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('bf994053-16ee-4e7a-aec6-7eddf1d57026'); return false;\">Science:</a> we study different sciences together with the main goal of removing possible barriers that readers may face due to their learning processes.</li><li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('867968ea-62d6-4a8a-b3a0-8b82c76d86bf'); return false;\">History:</a> studying history is complex, and often we cannot fully understand different peoples, leading to the illusion that there was only one \"civilization\" from a single place. Here we present various texts to help readers understand that we are one species.</li></ul></p>",
         "value": null,
         "date_time": [
            {
               "type": "gregory",
               "year": "2011",
               "month": "-1",
               "day": "-1"
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "introduction",
         "desc": "",
         "target": "",
         "page": "",
         "value_type": "",
         "html_value": "<p><h3>Families</h3>When grouping people into families, we often rely on cultural frameworks. As proposed by Morgan in the 19th century (Gregorian calendar), there are distinct types of families (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ebf06437-05d8-4153-8faf-97aa6a4a9acb'); return false;\">Engels, Frederick, <htdate0>, pp. 712 - 719</a>):</p><p><ol><li><b>The Consanguine Family</b>: The earliest form, in which descendants of a single couple were both siblings and spouses.</li><li><b>The Punaluan Family</b>: Characterized first by the exclusion of parent-child relationships, followed by the prohibition of sibling unions.</li><li><b>The Pairing Family</b>: Men cohabited with a primary wife while maintaining additional marital ties, whereas women had limited autonomy. Separation was straightforward, with children typically remaining with their mother.</li><li><b>The Monogamous Family</b>: A nuclear structure comprising a father, mother, and children.</li></ol></p><p>Notably, monogamy arose from economic imperatives rather than romantic love or natural inclination. While Roman women held higher status than their Greek counterparts, the Germanic peoples later reshaped marital institutions. Romantic marriage became widespread only during the European Middle Ages (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ebf06437-05d8-4153-8faf-97aa6a4a9acb'); return false;\">Engels, Frederick, <htdate1>, pp. 719 - 729</a>).</p><p>Additionally, bearing a surname today does not guarantee direct descent from its earliest bearers or confer any right to a familial coat of arms.</p>",
         "value": null,
         "date_time": [
            {
               "type": "gregory",
               "year": "1988",
               "month": "-1",
               "day": "-1"
            },
            {
