               "month": "-1",
               "day": "-1"
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "surname_patronymic",
         "desc": "",
         "target": "",
         "page": "",
         "value_type": "",
         "html_value": "<p><h4>Anachronisms in Surnames</h4>Beyond the challenges of categorizing families and understanding historical self-identification, late-medieval nobiliaries and fabricated genealogies often erroneously assign surnames without primary evidence of their historical use.</p><p>To mitigate possible anachronisms, the table below summarizes the use of surnames and patronymics in the Iberian Peninsula:</p>",
         "value": null,
         "date_time": null
      },
      {
         "id": "table_period",
         "desc": "",
         "target": "",
         "page": "",
         "value_type": "",
         "html_value": "<p><p><table class=\"mathexample\"> <tr><th>Period</th><th>Observacion</th><th>Patronymic</th><th>Surname</th></tr> <tr><td><htdate0> - <htdate1></td><td>In this period, there was no usage of patronymics or surnames.</td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr> <tr><td><htdate2> - <htdate3></td><td>As in the previous period, patronymics and surnames were also not used.</td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr> <tr><td style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"><htdate4> - <htdate5></td><td>Period of Arab conquest; the royal family avoided patronymics, but the nobility adopted them.</td><td style=\"vertical-align:middle;\">Yes</td><td style=\"vertical-align:middle;\">No</td></tr> <tr><td style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"><htdate6> - <htdate7></td><td>Initially, both patronymics and surnames were used, with a gradual transition to surnames only.</td><td style=\"vertical-align:middle;\">Yes</td><td style=\"vertical-align:middle;\">Yes</td></tr> </table></p>",
